ğŸ“– **Description:**
    The `c99` command is a compiler for C language code. It's used to convert source code written in C into executable programs. Specifically, `c99` compiles code according to the C99 standard.

âš™ï¸ **Options:**
    ğŸ”¹ `-o <program-name>` --> ğŸ“ Specifies the name of the executable program. If this option is not used, the default name will be `a.out`.
    ğŸ”¹ `-Wall`            --> âš ï¸ Shows all warnings. Using this option is very useful for finding potential errors in the code.
    ğŸ”¹ `-c`               --> ğŸ“¦ Only compiles the files and doesn't link them. This option is used to create object files (`.o`) for later use.
    ğŸ”¹ `-l<library>` --> ğŸ“š Specifies libraries to link. For example, `-lm` is used to link the math library.

ğŸ›  **Examples:**

    $ c99 hello.c

    ğŸ”¹ Compiles the file `hello.c` and creates the program `a.out`.

    $ c99 -o hello hello.c

    ğŸ”¹ Compiles the file `hello.c` and creates the program `hello`.

    $ c99 -Wall hello.c

    ğŸ”¹ Compiles the file `hello.c` while showing all warnings.

    $ c99 -c my_function.c

    ğŸ”¹ Compiles `my_function.c` and creates the object file `my_function.o`.

    $ c99 main.c my_function.o -o program

    ğŸ”¹ Compiles `main.c`, links `my_function.o`, and creates the program `program`.

âœ… **Simple Example:**

    $ c99 -o myprogram mycode.c -lm

    ğŸ”¹ This command compiles `mycode.c`, links it with the math library, and creates an executable program named `myprogram`. Using `-lm` is necessary if your code uses functions from the math library, such as `sqrt()`.
